WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:13.280
Oxford Bookworms, Stage 1. The Phantom of the Opera by Jennifer Bassett. Published and

00:13.280 --> 00:25.000
copyright Oxford University Press 1994. The Opera House in Paris is a very famous and

00:25.000 --> 00:32.520
beautiful building. It is the biggest opera house in the world. Work on the building began

00:32.520 --> 00:45.720
in 1861, finished in 1875 and cost 47 million francs. It has 17 floors, 10 above the ground

00:45.720 --> 00:54.680
and 7 under the ground. Behind and under the stage there are stairs and passages and many

00:54.680 --> 01:02.360
many rooms. Dressing rooms for the singers and the dancers. Rooms for the stage workers,

01:02.360 --> 01:10.680
the opera dresses and shoes. There are more than 2500 doors in the building. You can walk

01:10.680 --> 01:18.360
for hours and never see daylight under the Paris Opera House. And the Opera House has a ghost,

01:19.080 --> 01:27.800
a phantom, a man in black clothes. He is a body without a head, or a head without a body.

01:28.920 --> 01:34.680
He has a yellow face, he has no nose, he has black holes for eyes.

01:36.840 --> 01:45.400
This is the true story of the Phantom of the Opera. It begins one day in 1880 in the

01:45.400 --> 01:52.120
dancer's dressing room.

01:55.160 --> 02:04.120
Chapter One. The Dancers. Quick, quick, close the door. It's him.

02:05.640 --> 02:13.400
Annie Sirelli ran into the dressing room, her face white. One of the girls ran and closed the

02:13.400 --> 02:17.080
door and then they all turned to Annie Sirelli.

02:18.040 --> 02:22.520
Who? Where? What's the matter? They cried.

02:23.720 --> 02:33.080
It's the ghost. Annie said. In the passage I saw him. He came through the wall in front of me

02:34.040 --> 02:42.920
and and I saw his face. Most of the girls were afraid but one of them

02:42.920 --> 02:45.400
a tall girl with black hair laughed.

02:47.000 --> 02:54.520
Po, she said. Everybody says they see the opera ghost but there isn't really a ghost.

02:55.480 --> 03:03.640
You saw a shadow on the wall but she did not open the door or look into the passage.

03:03.880 --> 03:14.360
Lots of people see him, a second girl said. Joseph bouquet saw him two days ago. Don't you remember?

03:15.720 --> 03:24.600
Then all the girls began to talk at once. Joseph says the ghost is tall and he wears a black

03:24.680 --> 03:33.720
evening coat. He has the head of a dead man with a yellow face and no nose and no eyes,

03:33.720 --> 03:40.440
only black holes. Then little Meg Sirei spoke for the first time.

03:42.120 --> 03:47.720
Don't talk about him. He doesn't like it. My mother told me.

03:48.520 --> 03:56.120
Your mother, the girl with black hair said. What does your mother know about the ghost?

03:57.960 --> 04:04.440
She says that Joseph bouquet is a fool. The ghost doesn't like people talking about him

04:05.240 --> 04:10.440
and one day Joseph bouquet is going to be sorry. Very sorry.

04:11.320 --> 04:18.600
But what does your mother know? Tell us! Tell us! All the girls cried.

04:20.520 --> 04:26.520
Oh dear, said Meg. But please don't say a word to anyone.

04:27.880 --> 04:33.000
You know my mother is the doorkeeper for some of the boxes in the opera house.

04:33.960 --> 04:44.040
Well box five is the ghost's box. He watches the operas from that box and sometimes

04:44.040 --> 04:51.960
he leaves flowers for my mother. The ghost has a box and leaves flowers in it.

04:53.000 --> 04:59.000
Oh Meg, your mother's telling you stories. How can the ghost have a box?

04:59.960 --> 05:08.440
It's true. It's true, I tell you. Meg said. Nobody buys tickets for box five,

05:08.440 --> 05:15.000
but the ghost always comes to it on opera nights. So somebody does come there.

05:15.960 --> 05:21.480
Why no! The ghost comes, but there is nobody there.

05:22.120 --> 05:29.720
The dancers looked at Meg. But how does your mother know? One of them asked.

05:30.920 --> 05:37.480
There's no man in a black evening coat with a yellow face. That's all wrong.

05:38.680 --> 05:49.480
My mother never sees the ghost in box five, but she hears him. He talks to her, but there is nobody there.

05:51.480 --> 05:55.240
And he doesn't like people talking about him.

05:57.080 --> 06:02.200
But that evening the dancers could not stop talking about the opera ghost.

06:03.480 --> 06:08.920
They talked before the opera, all through the opera and after the opera,

06:10.200 --> 06:15.960
but they talked very quietly and they looked behind them before they spoke.

06:15.960 --> 06:21.960
When the opera finished, the girls went back to their dressing room.

06:23.480 --> 06:30.840
Suddenly they heard somebody in the passage and Madame Girie Meg's mother ran into the room.

06:31.960 --> 06:39.640
She was a fat motherly woman with a red happy face, but tonight her face was white.

06:40.440 --> 06:46.280
Oh girls! She cried. Joseph Bouquet is dead!

06:47.640 --> 06:52.360
You know he works a long way down on the fourth floor under the stage.

06:53.400 --> 07:00.040
The other stage workers found his dead body there an hour ago, with a rope around his neck.

07:00.200 --> 07:13.320
It's the ghost ride Meg Girie. The ghost killed him.

07:17.160 --> 07:21.080
Chapter 2 The Directors of the Opera House

07:21.880 --> 07:30.200
The opera house was famous and the directors of the opera house were very important men.

07:31.720 --> 07:35.160
It was the first week of work for the two new directors,

07:35.960 --> 07:39.640
Monsieur Armain-Morshammer and Monsieur Fumerechard.

07:41.320 --> 07:46.520
In the director's office the next day, the two men talked about Joseph Bouquet.

07:46.520 --> 07:54.760
It was an accident, Monsieur Armain-Morshammer said angrily, or Bouquet killed himself.

07:56.040 --> 08:01.080
An accident killed himself, Monsieur Fumerechard.

08:02.040 --> 08:07.800
Which story do you want, my friend? Or do you want the story of the ghost?

08:08.760 --> 08:13.000
Don't talk to me about ghosts, Monsieur Armain-Morshammer said.

08:13.720 --> 08:21.640
We have 1,500 people working for us in this opera house and everybody is talking about the ghost.

08:22.440 --> 08:27.960
They are all mad. I don't want to hear about the ghost, okay?

08:29.400 --> 08:32.760
Monsieur Fumere looked at a letter on the table next to him.

08:33.560 --> 08:37.240
And what are we going to do about this letter, Armain?

08:38.360 --> 08:40.360
Do, cried Monsieur Armain.

08:41.000 --> 08:44.600
Why do nothing, of course? What can we do?

08:46.040 --> 08:50.040
The two men read the letter again. It wasn't very long.

08:51.800 --> 08:53.560
To the new directors.

08:54.680 --> 09:00.440
Because you are new in the opera house, I am writing to tell you some important things.

09:01.160 --> 09:07.720
Never sell tickets for Box 5. That is my box for every opera night.

09:09.480 --> 09:13.480
Madame Jiri, the doorkeeper, knows all about it.

09:14.680 --> 09:18.360
Also, I need money for my work in the opera house.

09:19.560 --> 09:24.440
I am not expensive and I am happy to take only 20,000 francs a month.

09:25.560 --> 09:28.520
That is all. But please remember,

09:29.480 --> 09:33.720
I can be a good friend, but a bad enemy.

09:34.920 --> 09:36.120
Oh, gee.

09:38.200 --> 09:43.160
Don't sell tickets for Box 5, 20,000 francs a month.

09:44.120 --> 09:46.360
Monsieur Armain was very angry again.

09:47.080 --> 09:51.240
That's the best box in the opera house and we need the money for Ma.

09:51.880 --> 09:55.080
And who is this? Oh, gee, eh? Tell me that.

09:55.080 --> 10:00.680
Opera ghost, of course, Miss Yuffur Ma said.

10:01.720 --> 10:06.360
But you're right, Armain. We can do nothing about this letter.

10:07.240 --> 10:14.760
It's a joke, a bad joke. Somebody thinks we are fools because we are new here.

10:15.800 --> 10:18.280
There are no ghosts in the opera house.

10:20.920 --> 10:23.880
The two men then talked about the opera for that night.

10:24.600 --> 10:29.160
It was Faust and usually La Calotta sang Margarita.

10:30.520 --> 10:33.880
La Calotta was Spanish and the best singer in Paris.

10:34.760 --> 10:37.880
But today La Calotta was ill.

10:39.480 --> 10:42.440
Everybody in Paris is going to be at the opera tonight,

10:43.000 --> 10:47.560
said Miss Yuffur Ma. And our best singer is ill suddenly.

10:48.200 --> 10:53.640
She writes a letter to us just this morning. She is ill. She cannot sing tonight.

10:54.600 --> 10:59.400
Don't get angry again, Armain. Miss Yuffur Ma said quickly.

11:00.680 --> 11:08.120
We have Christine Daye, that young singer from Norway. She can sing Margarita tonight.

11:08.120 --> 11:13.720
She has a good voice. But she's so young and nobody knows her.

11:14.360 --> 11:23.640
Nobody wants to listen to a new singer. Wait and see. Perhaps Daye can sing better than La Calotta.

11:24.600 --> 11:25.560
Who knows?

11:35.080 --> 11:38.040
Chapter 3 Christine Daye

11:39.960 --> 11:45.880
Miss Yuffur Ma was right. All Paris talked about the new Margarita in Faust,

11:46.520 --> 11:51.560
the girl with the beautiful voice, the girl with the voice of an angel.

11:52.360 --> 11:57.880
People loved her. They laughed and cried and called for more.

11:59.240 --> 12:03.320
Daye was wonderful, the best singer in the world.

12:05.000 --> 12:08.680
Behind the stage, Meg Jiri looked at Annie Sirelli.

12:10.120 --> 12:17.480
Christine Daye never sang like that before. She said to Annie, why was she so good tonight?

12:18.280 --> 12:22.680
Perhaps she's got a new music teacher, Annie said.

12:25.000 --> 12:28.040
The noise in the opera house went on for a long time.

12:29.560 --> 12:36.200
In Box 14, Philippe, the Compt de Chani turned to his younger brother and smiled.

12:37.640 --> 12:41.320
Well, Raul, what did you think of Daye tonight?

12:42.280 --> 12:52.440
Raul, the V Compt de Chani, was 21 years old. He had blue eyes and black hair and a wonderful smile.

12:53.720 --> 13:00.120
The Chani family was old and rich and many girls in Paris were in love with the young V Compt.

13:01.240 --> 13:07.000
But Raul was not interested in them. He smiled back at his brother.

13:07.160 --> 13:15.320
What can I say? Christine is an angel, that's all. I'm going to her dressing room to see her tonight.

13:16.440 --> 13:22.760
Philippe laughed. He was 20 years older than Raul and was more like a father than a brother.

13:23.720 --> 13:27.240
Ah, I understand, he said.

13:28.200 --> 13:33.560
You are in love. But this is your first night in Paris.

13:33.560 --> 13:40.360
Your first visit to the opera. How do you know Christine Daye?

13:42.440 --> 13:49.400
You remember four years ago when I was on holiday by the sea in Brittany? Raul said,

13:50.280 --> 13:57.800
Well, I met Christine there. I was in love with her then and I'm still in love with her today.

13:58.760 --> 14:02.840
The Compt de Chani looked at his brother.

14:04.120 --> 14:15.400
Hmm, I see, he said slowly. Well Raul, remember she is only an opera singer. We know nothing about her family.

14:17.080 --> 14:25.880
But Raul did not listen. To him, good families were not important and young men never listened

14:25.880 --> 14:33.400
to their older brothers. There were many people in Christine Daye's dressing room that night.

14:34.440 --> 14:42.120
But there was a doctor with Christine and her beautiful face looked white and ill. Raul went

14:42.120 --> 14:49.720
quickly across the room and took her hand. Christine, what's the matter? Are you ill?

14:50.600 --> 14:59.480
He went down on the floor by her chair. Don't you remember me? Raul de Chani, in Brittany?

15:01.160 --> 15:07.800
Christine looked at him and her blue eyes were afraid. She took her hand away.

15:09.320 --> 15:15.880
No, I don't know you. Please go away. I'm not well.

15:16.360 --> 15:23.720
Raul stood up, his face read. Before he could speak, the doctor said quickly,

15:24.120 --> 15:35.080
Yes, yes, please go away. Everybody, please leave the room. Madam Azel Daye needs to be quiet. She is very tired.

15:36.280 --> 15:41.080
He moved to the door and soon everybody left the room.

15:41.560 --> 15:50.520
Christine Daye was alone in her dressing room. Outside in the passage, the young v comp was angry

15:50.520 --> 16:01.160
and unhappy. How could Christine forget him? How could she say that to him? He waited for some minutes,

16:02.120 --> 16:12.200
then, very quietly and carefully, he went back to the door of her dressing room. But he did not open the door,

16:12.200 --> 16:17.480
because just then he heard a man's voice in the room.

16:17.480 --> 16:26.920
Christine, you must love me, the voice said. Then Raul heard Christine's voice.

16:27.880 --> 16:37.480
How can you talk like that when I sing only for you? Tonight, I gave everything to you, everything,

16:38.520 --> 16:44.680
and now I'm so tired. Her voice was unhappy and afraid.

16:44.680 --> 16:57.560
You sang like an angel, the man's voice said. Raul walked away, so that was the answer.

16:57.560 --> 17:07.640
Christine Daye had a lover. But why was her voice so unhappy? He waited in the shadows near her room.

17:08.360 --> 17:18.840
He wanted to see her lover, his enemy. After about ten minutes, Christine came out of her room,

17:18.840 --> 17:28.520
alone, and walked away down the passage. Raul waited, but no man came out after her.

17:28.520 --> 17:36.040
There was nobody in the passage, so Raul went quickly up to the door of the dressing room,

17:36.600 --> 17:44.280
opened it, and went in. He closed the door quietly behind him, then called out.

17:45.560 --> 17:49.480
Where are you? I know you're in here. Come out!

17:51.400 --> 17:58.600
There was no answer. Raul looked everywhere, under the chairs, behind all the clothes,

17:59.240 --> 18:05.880
in all the dark corners of the room. There was nobody there.

18:14.200 --> 18:17.880
Chapter 4 The Phantom is Angry

18:18.600 --> 18:28.680
That was Tuesday night. On Wednesday morning, Miss Yama and Miss Yafirma were happy men.

18:29.800 --> 18:34.280
Paris liked the new Margarita. Everything in life was good.

18:36.920 --> 18:45.560
The next opera night was Friday. It was Faust again, but this time with La Carlotta singing Margarita.

18:45.720 --> 18:54.680
By Wednesday afternoon, they were not so happy. A second letter arrived for them, from O.G.

18:54.680 --> 19:08.440
Why don't you listen to me? I am getting angry. Leave Box 5 free for me. And where are my 20,000 francs?

19:09.240 --> 19:20.440
On Friday, Daya must sing Margarita again. She is now the best singer in Paris. La Carlotta cannot sing.

19:21.400 --> 19:31.960
She has a very ugly voice, like a toad. Remember, I am a bad enemy. O.G.

19:32.760 --> 19:42.120
So, Therma, is this still a joke? Miss Yama shouted. What are we going to do now, eh?

19:42.120 --> 19:51.880
Is O.G. the director here, or are we? Don't shout, Therma. Said Miss Yafirma tiredly.

19:52.760 --> 19:59.960
I don't know the answers. Let's talk to Madame Jiri, the doorkeeper of Box 5.

20:00.920 --> 20:03.160
Perhaps she can help us.

20:05.080 --> 20:11.240
But Madame Jiri was not helpful. Madame Jiri was not afraid of ghosts,

20:11.960 --> 20:15.400
and she was not afraid of directors of opera houses.

20:17.640 --> 20:23.320
People say that you're a friend of the opera ghost, Madame Jiri. Miss Yama began.

20:24.200 --> 20:28.760
Tell us about him. Some people say he has no head.

20:30.280 --> 20:38.200
And some people say he has no body, said Miss Yafirma. What do you say, Madame Jiri?

20:40.280 --> 20:43.320
Madame Jiri looked at the two men and laughed.

20:45.320 --> 20:49.960
I say that the directors of the opera house are fools.

20:50.840 --> 20:58.360
What, Miss Yama shouted? He stood up, and his face was red and angry.

20:59.320 --> 21:06.520
Listen to me, woman! O, sit down, Arman, and listen, said Miss Yafirma.

21:08.440 --> 21:17.000
Why do you say that, Madame Jiri? Because, Miss Yir, the opera ghost is angry with you.

21:17.000 --> 21:26.280
When the ghost wants something, he must have it. He is clever and dangerous this ghost.

21:27.480 --> 21:35.640
The old directors before you, they knew that, oh yes. At first they tried to stop him.

21:36.760 --> 21:42.040
Then there were many accidents in the opera house, many strange accidents.

21:43.000 --> 21:52.280
And when did these accidents happen? When the ghost was angry. So, the old directors learnt very

21:52.280 --> 22:00.520
quickly. The ghost wants box five, he can have it every night. The ghost wants money.

22:01.320 --> 22:09.240
Let's give the money to him at once. Oh yes, the old directors understood very well.

22:10.200 --> 22:19.640
But we are the directors, not the opera ghost. Miss Yama shouted. He turned to Miss Yafirma.

22:20.600 --> 22:29.000
This woman is mad. Why do we listen to her? On Friday night, La Calotta is going to sing

22:29.000 --> 22:36.680
Margarita. And you and I, Therma, are going to watch the opera from box five.

22:37.320 --> 22:44.520
Well, we can try that, Armaa. But we don't want any accidents.

22:46.200 --> 22:48.680
Madame Jiri came nearer to the two men.

22:50.440 --> 22:56.760
Listen to me, she said quietly. Remember Joseph Bouquet?

22:57.800 --> 23:04.440
I tell you, the opera ghost is a good friend, but a bad enemy.

23:05.000 --> 23:14.440
The two men stared at her. Those words, Miss Yafirmaa said slowly.

23:15.640 --> 23:19.800
Why did you say those words, Madame Jiri?

23:20.840 --> 23:28.680
Because the ghost says them to me. I never see him, but I often hear him.

23:29.000 --> 23:36.840
He has a very nice voice, and he doesn't shout at people.

23:46.680 --> 23:49.960
Chapter 5 A Letter for Raul

23:50.520 --> 23:57.320
That Wednesday, a letter also arrived for the young Vikom Dushani.

23:58.760 --> 24:05.080
He opened the letter, saw the name at the bottom, and smiled for the first time that day.

24:06.840 --> 24:12.520
Dear Raul, of course I remember you. How could I forget you?

24:12.520 --> 24:19.480
Meet me on Thursday at three o'clock in the Tuilerly Gardens.

24:19.480 --> 24:25.080
Don't be angry with me, Raul, please. Christine Day.

24:25.080 --> 24:30.200
Raul put the letter carefully into his pocket.

24:30.200 --> 24:35.320
Angry? How could he be angry with an angel?

24:35.800 --> 24:42.200
On Thursday, he was in the Tuilerly Gardens by two o'clock.

24:43.720 --> 24:47.400
At ten past three, he began to feel unhappy.

24:48.680 --> 24:53.320
At half past three, he wanted to die, or to kill somebody.

24:55.000 --> 25:00.680
And then, she came. She ran through the gardens to him,

25:01.640 --> 25:05.160
and in a second, she was in his arms.

25:06.520 --> 25:13.080
Oh, Christine! He said again and again. Oh, Christine!

25:15.480 --> 25:20.200
They walked through the gardens together and talked for a long time.

25:21.480 --> 25:25.800
They remembered their happy weeks in Brittany four years ago.

25:26.760 --> 25:34.680
But, why did you go away, Christine? Raul asked. Why didn't you write to me?

25:36.040 --> 25:41.800
For a minute or two, Christine said nothing. Then, she said slowly,

25:43.080 --> 25:51.320
We were so young, you and I. I was just a poor singer from Norway,

25:51.960 --> 25:56.200
and you. You were the vikom, the shunny.

25:57.400 --> 25:59.560
I knew I could never be your wife.

26:01.080 --> 26:07.960
But I love you, Christine. No, shh. Listen to me, Raul, please.

26:09.480 --> 26:14.520
I went home to Norway, and a year later, my father died.

26:15.480 --> 26:20.760
I was very unhappy. But I came back to France, to Paris,

26:22.040 --> 26:27.400
I worked and worked at my singing, because I wanted to be an opera singer,

26:28.520 --> 26:33.240
not just a good singer, but the best opera singer in Paris.

26:34.760 --> 26:42.280
And now you are, Raul said. He smiled. All Paris is at your feet.

26:42.440 --> 26:46.920
Christine turned her face away, and said nothing.

26:48.600 --> 26:55.000
Christine, Raul said quietly. I want to ask you a question.

26:56.440 --> 27:02.520
Who was the man in your dressing room on Tuesday night? Tell me, please.

27:04.120 --> 27:09.320
Christine stopped and stared at him. Her face went white.

27:09.960 --> 27:17.640
What man? She whispered. There was no man in my dressing room on Tuesday night.

27:18.440 --> 27:24.680
Raul put his hand on her arm. I heard him, he said.

27:25.400 --> 27:32.840
I listened outside the door and heard a man's voice. Who was he?

27:33.720 --> 27:42.520
Don't ask me, Raul. There was a man's voice, yes. But there was no man in my room.

27:43.080 --> 27:50.920
It's true. Oh, Raul, I'm so afraid. Sometimes I want to die.

27:52.040 --> 27:59.080
Who is he? Tell me, Christine, please. I'm your friend. I can help you.

27:59.160 --> 28:02.360
I can help you. Tell me his name.

28:05.560 --> 28:11.720
I cannot tell you his name. It's a secret, whispered Christine.

28:13.480 --> 28:19.640
I never see him. I only hear his voice, but he is everywhere.

28:20.840 --> 28:27.720
He sees everything. He is everything. That's why I didn't speak to you on Tuesday night.

28:29.080 --> 28:33.240
He is my music teacher, Raul. He's a wonderful singer.

28:34.440 --> 28:40.440
I sang so well on Tuesday night because of him. I am famous because of him.

28:41.560 --> 28:49.720
He is my angel of music. And he says he loves me. How can I leave him?

28:59.720 --> 29:04.360
Chapter 6 La Calotta Singes Margarita

29:07.160 --> 29:15.720
On Friday morning La Calotta had her breakfast in bed. She drank her coffee and opened her morning letters.

29:17.080 --> 29:26.360
One letter had no name on it. It was very short. You are ill. You cannot sing Margarita tonight.

29:27.000 --> 29:37.800
Stay at home and don't go to the opera house. Accidents can happen. Do you want to lose your voice? Forever.

29:40.040 --> 29:46.920
La Calotta was very, very angry. She got out of bed at once and did not finish her breakfast.

29:47.560 --> 29:54.520
This is from Christine Dai's friends, she thought. They want her to sing again tonight.

29:55.560 --> 30:03.800
That Dai girl is going to be sorry for this. I, La Calotta, I am the best opera singer in Paris.

30:05.160 --> 30:09.480
And nothing is going to stop me singing Margarita tonight.

30:11.960 --> 30:16.120
At six o'clock that evening, the dancers were in their dressing room.

30:17.000 --> 30:21.880
They talked and laughed and put on their red and black dresses for Faust.

30:23.000 --> 30:25.160
But Meg Jiri was very quiet.

30:26.680 --> 30:30.280
What's the matter, Meg? Annie Sirelli asked.

30:31.880 --> 30:41.400
It's the opera ghost, Meg said. My mother says he's angry. She's afraid that something's going to happen tonight.

30:42.200 --> 30:49.160
Oh, poo. The girl with black hair said, who's afraid of an old ghost?

30:51.480 --> 30:58.360
An hour later, Miss Yerama and Miss Yerfirma went into box five and sat down.

30:59.560 --> 31:05.800
They were not afraid of ghosts. Of course not. There were no ghosts in the opera house.

31:06.120 --> 31:11.720
Then, Miss Yerama saw some flowers on the floor by the door of the box.

31:12.920 --> 31:18.920
Verma, he whispered. Did you put those flowers there?

31:20.120 --> 31:22.040
Miss Yerfirma looked.

31:22.920 --> 31:26.920
No, I didn't. He whispered back.

31:27.640 --> 31:31.640
Did you? Of course not to fall.

31:32.280 --> 31:34.840
Shh. The music's beginning.

31:36.440 --> 31:44.040
Larkar Lotta did not sing for the first hour. There were no strange voices in box five,

31:44.760 --> 31:47.080
and the two directors began to feel happier.

31:48.280 --> 31:54.760
Then Larkar Lotta came out onto the stage, and Miss Yerfirma looked at Miss Yerama.

31:56.280 --> 32:00.600
Did you hear a voice just then? He asked quietly.

32:01.560 --> 32:12.280
No, Miss Yerama said, but he looked behind him twice, then three times, and suddenly felt cold.

32:14.600 --> 32:22.760
Larkar Lotta sang and sang, and nothing happened. Then, she began a beautiful love song.

32:22.760 --> 32:28.920
My love begins to Gawk.

32:30.760 --> 32:35.000
Everybody stared. What was the matter with Carlotta's voice?

32:36.280 --> 32:39.480
What was that strange noise? Gawk.

32:41.240 --> 32:44.360
Carlotta stopped and began the song again.

32:45.960 --> 32:50.440
My love begins to Gawk.

32:50.840 --> 32:57.240
Gawk. I cannot forget my Gawk.

32:58.440 --> 33:03.480
It was the noise of a toad. People began to talk and laugh.

33:04.520 --> 33:11.480
Miss Yerfirma put his head in his hands. Then he felt Miss Yerama's hand on his arm.

33:12.600 --> 33:18.440
There was a voice in the box with them. A man's voice. Laughing.

33:19.240 --> 33:28.440
Poor Carlotta tried again and again. I cannot forget my Gawk.

33:30.440 --> 33:38.440
Then the two directors heard the voice again, behind them, in front of them, everywhere.

33:40.440 --> 33:46.440
Her singing tonight is going to bring down the chandelier.

33:49.400 --> 33:55.560
The two directors looked up at the top of the opera house. Their faces were white.

33:56.760 --> 34:04.680
The famous chandelier, with its thousand lights, broke away from its ropes and crashed down onto

34:04.680 --> 34:13.080
the people below. That was a terrible night for the Paris Opera House. One woman was killed by

34:13.080 --> 34:19.800
the chandelier and many people were hurt. The opera house closed for two weeks

34:20.840 --> 34:24.360
and La Carlotta never sang again.

34:32.120 --> 34:35.320
Chapter 7. My Angel of Music

34:35.320 --> 34:45.400
For a week Raul saw Christine every day. Some days Christine was quiet and unhappy.

34:46.440 --> 34:52.440
Some days she laughed and sang. She never wanted to talk about the opera house,

34:53.160 --> 35:00.840
or her singing, or Raul's love for her. Raul was very afraid for her.

35:01.640 --> 35:13.640
Who, or what, was this strange teacher, this man's voice, her angel of music.

35:16.440 --> 35:25.480
Then one day there was no Christine. She was not at her home, not at the opera house,

35:26.440 --> 35:33.160
not at their meeting places. Raul looked everywhere and asked everybody.

35:34.280 --> 35:37.960
Where was Christine dying? But nobody knew.

35:40.280 --> 35:47.000
Two days before the opera house opened again, a letter arrived for Raul. It was from Christine.

35:47.320 --> 35:54.280
Meet me in an hour at the top of the opera house on the tenth floor.

35:56.600 --> 36:01.960
The tenth floor of the opera house was a dangerous place. There were hundreds of

36:01.960 --> 36:08.200
ropes going down to the stage below. It was a long, long way down.

36:10.360 --> 36:16.360
Raul and Christine sat in a dark corner and Raul took Christine's hands

36:17.720 --> 36:19.880
her face was white and tired.

36:22.680 --> 36:28.760
Listen Raul, she said quietly. I'm going to tell you everything,

36:30.120 --> 36:34.920
but this is our last meeting. I can never see you again.

36:34.920 --> 36:46.920
No, Christine. Raul cried. I love you. And we shh, quietly. Perhaps he can hear us.

36:48.120 --> 36:55.000
He's everywhere in the opera house, Raul. Who? What are you talking about, Christine?

36:55.880 --> 37:07.000
My angel of music. I couldn't meet you last Saturday because he came for me and took me away.

37:08.680 --> 37:14.840
I was in my dressing room in the opera house and suddenly he was there in front of me.

37:16.360 --> 37:24.840
I saw the voice for the first time. He wore black evening clothes and a mask over his face.

37:25.640 --> 37:32.760
He took me through many secret doors and passages down, down under the opera house.

37:34.440 --> 37:42.040
There is a lake down there, a big lake. The waters are black and cold.

37:43.880 --> 37:51.560
He took me across the lake in a boat to his house. He lives there Raul in a house on the lake,

37:52.520 --> 38:00.840
under the opera house. Raul stared at her. Was his beautiful Christine mad?

38:02.280 --> 38:14.600
Christine saw his face and said quickly, it's true Raul. It's true. And he is the phantom of the opera,

38:15.560 --> 38:21.720
but he's not a ghost. He's not an angel of music. He's a man.

38:23.320 --> 38:29.240
His name is Eric, and he loves me. He wants me to be his wife.

38:30.200 --> 38:38.680
No Raul, listen. There is more. He told me all this in his house, in a beautiful room.

38:39.560 --> 38:47.800
He said that no woman could ever love him, because of his face. He was so unhappy.

38:49.000 --> 38:54.760
Then he took off his mask and I saw his face.

38:56.440 --> 39:01.240
She began to cry and Raul put his arms around her.

39:02.040 --> 39:13.400
Oh Raul, he has the most terrible face. It is so ugly. I wanted to scream and run away.

39:14.600 --> 39:23.080
But where could I run too? He has the face of a dead man Raul, but he is not dead.

39:23.160 --> 39:31.640
He has no nose, just two black holes in his yellow face, and his eyes.

39:31.640 --> 39:40.680
Sometimes they are black holes. Sometimes they have a terrible red light.

39:40.680 --> 39:47.080
She put her face in her hands for a second. Then she said,

39:47.560 --> 39:57.640
I stayed in his house for five days. He was very good to me, and I felt sorry for him Raul.

39:59.400 --> 40:05.560
He wants me to love him, and I told him, I told him,

40:06.520 --> 40:14.120
No Christine, no. You're going to be my wife. Come away with me at once. Today,

40:15.080 --> 40:16.920
you can't go back to him.

40:19.080 --> 40:27.880
But I must, Christine said quietly. He knows about you Raul. He knows about us.

40:29.400 --> 40:34.120
He says he's going to kill you. I must go back to him.

40:34.920 --> 40:42.600
Never said Raul. I love you, Christine, and I'm going to kill this Eric.

40:50.680 --> 40:56.360
The word whispered around the opera house. Raul and Christine stared.

40:57.000 --> 41:08.440
What was that? Raul said afraid. Was that his voice? Where did it come from?

41:08.440 --> 41:18.440
I'm afraid Raul. Christine whispered. I'm singing Margarita again on Saturday. What's going to happen?

41:19.320 --> 41:28.280
This, Raul said. After the opera on Saturday night, you and I are going away together.

41:28.280 --> 41:34.440
Come on. Let's go down now. I don't like it up here.

41:36.280 --> 41:44.440
They went carefully along a dark passage to some stairs. Then suddenly stopped. There was

41:44.520 --> 41:54.040
a man in front of them. A tall man in a long dark coat and a black hat. He turned and looked at them.

41:56.680 --> 42:05.480
No. Not these stairs, he said. Go to the stairs at the front and go quickly.

42:06.360 --> 42:11.960
Christine turned and ran. Raul ran after her.

42:13.480 --> 42:15.560
Who was that man? He asked.

42:16.760 --> 42:23.080
It's the Persian, Christine answered. But who is he? What's his name?

42:24.040 --> 42:26.680
Why did he tell us to go to the front stairs?

42:28.600 --> 42:34.680
Nobody knows his name. He's just the Persian. He's always in the opera house.

42:35.960 --> 42:40.040
I think he knows about Eric, but he never talks about him.

42:41.320 --> 42:46.040
Perhaps he saw Eric on those stairs and wanted to help us.

42:48.120 --> 42:55.000
Hand in hand, they ran quickly down the stairs, through passages, then more stairs and more

42:55.000 --> 43:01.240
passages. At one of the little back doors to the opera house, they stopped.

43:01.960 --> 43:11.960
On Saturday night then, after the opera, Raul said, I'm going to take you away and marry you.

43:13.640 --> 43:24.120
Christine looked up into his face. Yes, Raul. Then they kissed, thereby the door of the opera house.

43:25.080 --> 43:26.840
Their first kiss.

43:35.640 --> 43:39.720
Chapter 8. Where is Christine Daye?

43:42.680 --> 43:47.800
On Saturday morning, Comte Philippe looked across the breakfast table at his brother.

43:48.600 --> 43:58.280
Don't do it, Raul. Please, all this talk about ghosts and phantoms, I think the girl is mad.

43:59.400 --> 44:03.880
She's not mad, and I'm going to marry her, Raul said.

44:05.160 --> 44:12.440
She's only a little opera singer, Philippe said unhappily. And she's very young.

44:13.320 --> 44:17.560
Are you still going to love her in ten or twenty years' time?

44:19.320 --> 44:22.360
Raul drank his coffee and did not answer.

44:25.720 --> 44:29.240
There were two more unhappy faces in the opera house, too.

44:30.920 --> 44:36.680
The directors now understood about OG. They didn't want any more accidents.

44:37.560 --> 44:47.000
Box 5 is free tonight for OG. Daye is singing Margarita, and here is 20,000 francs.

44:47.000 --> 44:52.600
Madam Jiri can leave the money in Box 5 for him. Is that everything?

44:53.560 --> 44:55.640
Miss Yama asked Miss Yafirma.

44:57.560 --> 45:04.280
It's a lot of money, Miss Yafirma said unhappily. He thought for a minute.

45:05.240 --> 45:13.000
What about some flowers in Box 5? Madam Jiri says that OG likes flowers.

45:14.200 --> 45:19.000
OG can bring his own flowers. Shouted Miss Yama.

45:20.760 --> 45:26.360
The evening began well. The chandelier was now back in place with new ropes.

45:27.400 --> 45:33.480
All Paris was in the opera house. Everybody wanted to hear Christine Daye's voice again.

45:34.920 --> 45:40.440
People also knew about the love story between Christine Daye and the VICOM de Shawnee.

45:41.640 --> 45:48.840
There are no love secrets in Paris. People watched the comp and the VICOMT in Box 14 with interest.

45:50.520 --> 45:55.080
Young men from families like de Shawnee do not marry opera singers.

45:58.200 --> 46:03.800
When Christine came onto the stage, her face was white and she looked afraid.

46:04.920 --> 46:13.560
But she sang like an angel. Ah, what a voice. All Paris was in love with Christine Daye.

46:15.320 --> 46:22.360
She began to sing the famous love song. Suddenly, every light in the opera house went out.

46:23.880 --> 46:32.120
For a second, nobody moved or spoke. Then, a woman screamed and all the lights came on again.

46:33.080 --> 46:41.400
But Christine Daye was no longer on the stage. She was not behind the stage. She was not under the stage.

46:42.600 --> 46:51.640
Nobody could find her. The opera house went mad. Everybody ran here and there shouted and called.

46:53.080 --> 46:59.160
In the director's office, people ran in and out. The police came and asked questions.

46:59.960 --> 47:01.960
But nobody could answer the questions.

47:03.240 --> 47:08.360
Miss Yer Armand got angry and shouted and Miss Yer Ferman told him to be quiet.

47:09.560 --> 47:14.120
Then Madam Jiri arrived in the office with her daughter Meg.

47:15.720 --> 47:19.240
Go away, woman. Miss Yer Armand shouted.

47:21.320 --> 47:26.760
Miss Yer, there are three people missing now. Madam Jiri said,

47:27.640 --> 47:34.200
Meg, tell the directors your story. This was Meg's story.

47:37.480 --> 47:45.480
When the lights went out, we were just behind the stage. We heard a scream. I think it was Christine

47:45.480 --> 47:54.920
Daye's voice. Then the lights came back on. But Christine wasn't there. We were very afraid.

47:55.800 --> 48:01.320
And we began to run back to our dressing room. There were people running everywhere.

48:02.680 --> 48:09.320
Then we saw the Viconf de Chani. His face was red and he was very angry.

48:10.360 --> 48:14.040
Where's Christine? Where's Christine? He shouted.

48:15.320 --> 48:23.400
Suddenly the Persian came up behind him and took his arm. He said something to the Viconf

48:23.480 --> 48:26.120
and they went into Christine Daye's dressing room.

48:27.560 --> 48:34.600
Yes. And then, Miss Yer Ferman said quickly, what happened next?

48:36.440 --> 48:45.320
Nobody knows. Meg's face was white. We looked into Christine Daye's dressing room, but

48:46.120 --> 48:48.120
but there was nobody there.

48:58.520 --> 49:02.520
Chapter 9. The House on the Lake

49:04.520 --> 49:13.480
When the lights came on, Raul ran. He ran downstairs and along passages, through the opera

49:13.560 --> 49:19.640
house to the back of the stage. In the passage outside Christine's dressing room,

49:20.360 --> 49:22.040
a hand took his arm.

49:23.880 --> 49:29.480
What's the matter, my young friend? Where are you running to so quickly?

49:31.000 --> 49:36.920
Raul turned and saw the long face of the Persian under his black hat.

49:37.720 --> 49:48.520
Christine, Raul said quickly. Eric's got her. Where is she? Help me. How do I get to his house on the lake?

49:50.120 --> 49:56.520
Come with me, said the Persian. They went quickly into Christine's dressing room.

49:58.200 --> 50:02.600
The Persian closed the door and went to the big mirror on one wall.

50:02.600 --> 50:08.280
There's only one door into this room. Raul began.

50:09.400 --> 50:17.000
Wait. The Persian said. He put his hands on the big mirror, first here, then there.

50:18.440 --> 50:24.840
For a minute, nothing happened. Then, the mirror began to move and turn,

50:25.720 --> 50:30.600
and a big dark hole opened in it. Raul stared.

50:31.400 --> 50:42.120
Quick. Come with me. But be careful. The Persian said. I know Eric. I understand his secrets.

50:43.320 --> 50:48.760
Put your right hand up near your head, like this, and keep it there all the time.

50:50.360 --> 50:57.320
But why, Raul asked? Remember Joseph Bouquet and the rope around his neck.

50:58.280 --> 51:01.080
Eric is a clever man with ropes in the dark.

51:04.440 --> 51:09.400
They went down, down, down, under the opera house.

51:10.520 --> 51:17.160
They went through secret doors in the floors, then along passages and down dark stairs.

51:18.760 --> 51:23.080
The Persian listened carefully all the time for strange noises.

51:23.400 --> 51:34.520
When do we get to the lake? Raul whispered. We're not going by the lake. Eric watches it all the time.

51:35.400 --> 51:43.000
No. We go round the lake and get into Eric's house from the back. I know some secret doors.

51:44.920 --> 51:52.120
Soon, they were there. In the dark, the Persian felt the wall carefully with his hands.

51:54.040 --> 52:02.360
Here it is. He whispered. The wall moved under his hands and a small door opened.

52:03.640 --> 52:11.640
Very quietly, they went through. And then the door closed behind them. They could not get out.

52:14.040 --> 52:21.640
Inside the room it was very dark. They waited and listened. The Persian put his hands on the wall.

52:23.240 --> 52:31.720
Oh, no. He whispered. It was the wrong door. This is Eric's torture room, the room of mirrors.

52:32.600 --> 52:35.720
We are dead men, Vikantashani. Dead men.

52:37.960 --> 52:46.360
At first Raul did not understand, but he soon learnt. The lights came on and they heard a man's

52:46.360 --> 52:56.200
laugh. Eric knew they were there. The room was all mirrors, walls, floor, ceiling.

52:57.320 --> 53:03.640
There were pictures in the mirrors of trees and flowers and rivers. The pictures moved and

53:03.640 --> 53:12.600
danced in front of their eyes and the room was hot. It got hotter and hotter and hotter.

53:13.400 --> 53:21.320
Raul was thirsty, hot and thirsty and the rivers in the pictures danced and laughed at him.

53:22.680 --> 53:26.200
He closed his eyes, but the rivers still danced.

53:27.720 --> 53:33.400
Water. He needed water, but the mirrors laughed at him.

53:33.800 --> 53:47.160
Soon, he could not move or speak or open his eyes. He was not thirsty now, just tired, so tired.

53:49.160 --> 53:57.400
Oh, Christine, I'm sorry. He thought, I wanted to help you and now I'm dying.

53:58.040 --> 54:04.760
Through a mirror in the wall, Christine watched her lover in the torture room.

54:05.960 --> 54:10.040
Behind her, Eric stood with his hands on her arms.

54:11.560 --> 54:22.680
He's dying, Christine, dying. Watch him carefully. No, don't close your eyes. Watch him.

54:23.000 --> 54:30.200
Christine could not speak. She wanted to scream, but no words came.

54:31.320 --> 54:39.160
Then she found her voice again. How can you do this, Eric? Why don't you kill me?

54:41.160 --> 54:48.360
Because I love you, Christine. Marry me. Be my wife and love me.

54:49.240 --> 54:52.200
Then Raul and the Persian can live.

54:54.200 --> 55:04.040
Slowly, Christine turned. She looked into Eric's terrible, ugly face and spoke again very quietly.

55:05.880 --> 55:11.400
Yes, Eric. For this minute, I am your wife.

55:11.720 --> 55:21.480
She put her arms around Eric's neck and kissed him. Kissed him slowly and lovingly, on his ugly mouth.

55:22.840 --> 55:34.920
Then she took her arms away and said slowly, poor, unhappy, Eric. Eric stared at her.

55:35.720 --> 55:45.800
You kissed me. He whispered, I didn't ask you, but you kissed me. Really?

55:46.840 --> 55:57.320
Oh, Christine, I angel. That was my first kiss from a woman. Even my mother never kissed me.

55:58.120 --> 56:08.120
She gave me my first mask when I was two years old. She turned her face away from me every time I came near her.

56:10.120 --> 56:18.760
Eric put his ugly face in his hands and cried. Then he went down on the floor at Christine's feet.

56:19.720 --> 56:31.240
You are free, Christine. Free. Go away and marry your Raul and be happy. But remember, Eric, sometimes.

56:31.240 --> 56:38.280
Go now. Quickly. Take Raul and the Persian and go.

56:38.280 --> 56:51.800
Chapter 10. Madam Jiri visits the Persian.

56:54.520 --> 57:01.240
For weeks, all Paris talked about that night at the opera. Everybody asked questions,

57:01.960 --> 57:09.240
but nobody knew the answers. Where was Christine Daye? Where was the Vikomtashani?

57:10.440 --> 57:17.160
Were they alive or dead? And the Phantom of the Opera?

57:20.360 --> 57:27.640
Some weeks after that famous night, Madam Jiri went out one afternoon to a small house near the

57:27.720 --> 57:34.120
riverly gardens. She went in and up the stairs to some rooms at the top of the house.

57:35.480 --> 57:47.240
The Persian opened the door. Madam Jiri looked at him. My friend, you know the answers. Please

57:47.240 --> 57:56.200
tell me, are they alive or dead? Come in, the Persian said quietly.

57:57.720 --> 58:02.920
They sat down on some chairs by the window and looked out across the riverly gardens.

58:04.600 --> 58:13.720
Yes, the Persian said slowly. The Phantom is dead now. He did not want to live any longer.

58:14.600 --> 58:23.720
I saw his body three days ago, and because of that, I can talk to you about him. He cannot kill me now.

58:25.560 --> 58:37.160
So, the Phantom was really a man, Madam Jiri asked. Yes, his name was Eric. That was not his

58:37.160 --> 58:45.960
real name, of course. He was born in France, but I knew him in Persia. He was a famous builder,

58:45.960 --> 58:54.040
and I worked with him there. For a time, I was his friend, but not for long.

58:55.560 --> 59:03.640
When he came to Paris, I came after him. I wanted to watch him. He was a very clever,

59:03.640 --> 59:12.600
very dangerous man. He could be in two or three places at the same time. He could be in one place,

59:13.320 --> 59:19.560
and his voice could come from another place. He could do many clever things with ropes and mirrors

59:20.120 --> 59:28.280
and secret doors. You see, he helped to build the opera house. He built secret passages underground

59:28.920 --> 59:35.480
and his secret house on the lake. He could not live in the outside world because of his terrible

59:35.480 --> 59:46.360
ugly face. Unhappy, Eric. We can feel sorry for him, Madam Jiri. He was so clever and so ugly.

59:47.880 --> 59:55.560
People screamed when they saw his face, and so he lived this strange life, half man, half Phantom.

59:55.960 --> 01:00:08.040
But he was a man in the end. He wanted a woman's love. He stopped, and Madam Jiri asked quietly,

01:00:09.960 --> 01:00:20.280
and Christine Daye, and they comped Raoul. What happened to them? The Persian smiled.

01:00:21.160 --> 01:00:29.960
Ah, yes. What happened to young Raoul and the beautiful Christine? Who knows?

01:00:33.400 --> 01:00:40.200
Nobody in Paris ever saw Raoul and Christine again. Perhaps they took a train to the north,

01:00:40.920 --> 01:00:48.920
and lived a quiet, happy life together there. Perhaps Christine's wonderful voice is still singing,

01:00:48.920 --> 01:00:55.720
somewhere in the cold and beautiful mountains of Norway. Who knows?

